The peer is an independent OpenSSL consumer of the standard DTLS APIs.

Protocol behavior was selected from OpenConnect commit
2035601b64a5360a46d18e08937e7f654b3230f2:

- openssl-dtls.c start_dtls_handshake() certificate verification and the
  F5 pre-v16 DTLS 1.0 version restriction
- f5.c parse_options() DTLS version and transport selection
- fortinet.c parse_fortinet_xml_config() DTLS 1.2 selection

The peer shares no implementation with the production Go client.

The Pion v3.1.5 callback limitation was verified in its cached source:
certificate.go defines CertificateRequestInfo with only AcceptableCAs, and
flight5handler.go flight5Generate copies only CertificateAuthoritiesNames into
that value even though MessageCertificateRequest also contains
SignatureHashAlgorithms. The adapter therefore reports no DTLS 1.2 peer
signature schemes to tls.Config.GetClientCertificate instead of synthesizing
them.

resume_peer.c independently constructs the OpenSSL server-side session state
for Cisco's DTLS 1.2 injected abbreviated-resumption exchange. It is used only
as a real OpenSSL oracle for the CBC cipher families which ocserv cannot expose
through that proprietary exchange.
